To normalize a vector, you divide each component of the vector by its magnitude (or length) to obtain a new vector with a magnitude of one. The formula for normalization is:

\vec{v_n} = \frac{\vec{v}}{|\vec{v}|}

where v is the original vector and |v| represents its magnitude or length. For example, if your original vector was [3, 4], first calculate its magnitude using the Pythagorean theorem: sqrt(3^2 + 4^2). Then, divide each element in the original vector by this value: [0.6, 0.8]. Finally, your normalized vector would be [0.6, 0.8].

