    let n = numbers[i];
    // Edge case: Number less than or equal to 1 cannot be prime
    if (n <= 1) continue;

    // Checking if n is divisible by anything from 2 through sqrt(n), inclusive
    for (let j = 2; j <= Math.sqrt(n); j++) {
      if (n % j === 0) break;
    } else return console.log(n);
  }
}

// Example usage
checkPrime([7, 8, 3, 9, 4]); // Output: 7
```

This implementation first iterates over each element `n` of the given array. It then performs two nested loops to determine whether `n` is a prime number. The outer loop checks whether `n` is greater than 1. If not, the current element has already been checked before moving on to the next iteration of the main loop, so we skip ahead using the `continue` statement.

The inner loop iterates over all possible divisors `j` of `n`, starting at 2 and ending at the square root of `n`. If any such divisor is found during this loop, we immediately return since `n` is clearly composite rather than prime. Otherwise, once the inner loop completes without finding any divisors of `n`, the original number is indeed prime, so we output it to the console using `console.log()`. 

Note that there are many different ways to implement primality checking in JavaScript, depending on your specific needs and preferences. This particular approach uses simple algorithms to compute factorial and square roots, which may not always be the most efficient solution. However, they should suffice for small arrays with relatively modest-sized numbers. For larger inputs or more demanding use cases, you might want to explore alternative approaches like Miller-Rabin testing, Sieve of Eratosthenes, etc.

